  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Writer of epigrams, to whom the Anthologia Palatina 
    ascribes a love poem (Anth. Pal. 5,49) that, by virtue of its style and vocabulary (though not
    because of its obscene tone), appears to belong to the ‘Garland’ of Philip, and also an ecphrastic 
    epigram, a polished description of a Tantalus figure on a cup (16,89). In the first case the lemmatist 
    added a τοῦ δικαίου to Γάλλου that probably conceals the nomen gentile Tudicius (cf. Cic. Clu. 70) ─ 
    but it is not evidence that it is the same writer. As author or addressee of the second epigram,
    Cornelius [II 18] Gallus (Virgil's friend, who committed suicide in 26 BC) has been suggested...." 
    Albiani, Maria Grazia (Bologna). "Gallus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2010. Brill Online. Tufts University Library</mads:note> 
